Added the fastfilereader.The main thing of interest in here is the Mapper, which is a simpleninterface to mmap a file.  It has implementations for both Unix andnWindows.  it will probably end up in EventMachine, but for now we'rensticking it with Swiftiply since it is needed by the code that handlesnlarge file transfers.n
close() undeclared error on gcc 3.2.3 fixed.  Needed unistd.h.

Merge of branches/raggi Most notable work and patches by Aman Gupta, Roger Pack, and James Tucker. Patches / Tickets also submitted by: Jeremy Evans, aanand, darix, mmmurf, danielaquino, macournoyer.  - Moved docs into docs/ dir  - Major refactor of rakefile, added generic rakefile helpers in tasks  - Added example CPP build rakefile in tasks/cpp.rake  - Moved rake tests out to tasks/tests.rake  - Added svn ignores where appropriate  - Fixed jruby build on older java platforms  - Gem now builds from Rakefile rather than directly via extconf  - Gem unified for jruby, C++ and pure ruby.  - Correction for pure C++ build, removing ruby dependency  - Fix for CYGWIN builds on ipv6  - Major refactor for extconf.rb  - Working mingw builds  - extconf optionally uses pkg_config over manual configuration  - extconf builds for 1.9 on any system that has 1.9  - extconf no longer links pthread explicitly  - looks for kqueue on all *nix systems  - better error output on std::runtime_error, now says where it came from  - Fixed some tests on jruby  - Added test for general send_data flaw, required for a bugfix in jruby build  - Added timeout to epoll tests  - Added fixes for java reactor ruby api  - Small addition of some docs in httpclient.rb and httpcli2.rb  - Some refactor and fixes in smtpserver.rb  - Added parenthesis where possible to avoid excess ruby warnings  - Refactor of $eventmachine_library logic for accuracy and maintenance, jruby  - EM::start_server now supports unix sockets  - EM::connect now supports unix sockets  - EM::defer @threadqueue now handled more gracefully  - Added better messages on exceptions raised  - Fix edge case in timer fires  - Explicitly require buftok.rb  - Add protocols to autoload, rather than require them all immediately  - Fix a bug in pr_eventmachine for outbound_q  - Refactors to take some of the use of defer out of tests.  - Fixes in EM.defer under start/stop conditions. Use close() instead of closesocket() to prevent FD leaks on windows.This is due to ruby.h/defines.h/win32.h in the ruby source redefiningnall the socket functions to call rb_w32_* functions instead. This meansnthe return value of socket() is not a win32 SOCKET handle, but insteadna file descriptor wrapper that the ruby VM owns. We must call close()n(which invokes rb_w32_close) to dispose of it correctly.n

Delete Java reactor's associated java tests and application layer. These are out of date, unmaintained and there is no point in keeping them around.The Java reactor (and the C++ reactor) were both initially designed tonbe usable outside of Ruby. However, no one actually does and keeping (ornpretending to keep) compatibility layers just slows down development andnmakes the experience of using and developing EM for ruby more painful. Inwould prefer instead to focus development efforts on the Ruby use-casenspecifically.nnThat said, these files are and will remain in the Git history if someonenwishes to use them.n

Segfault fix for pipesEventMachine relies on the fact that when close(fd)nis called that the fd is removed from anynepoll event queues.nnHowever, this is not *always* the behavior of close(fd)nnSee man 4 epoll Q6/A6 and then consider what happensnwhen using pipes with eventmachine.n(As is often done when communicating with a subprocess)nnThe pipes end up looking like:nnls -l /proc/<pid>/fdn...nlr-x------ 1 root root 64 2011-08-19 21:31 3 -> pipe:[940970]nl-wx------ 1 root root 64 2011-08-19 21:31 4 -> pipe:[940970]nnThis meets the critera from man 4 epoll Q6/A4 for notnremoving fds from epoll event queues until all fdsnthat reference the underlying file have been removed.nnIf the EventableDescriptor associated with fd 3 is deleted,nits dtor will call EventableDescriptor::Close(),nwhich will call ::close(int fd).nnHowever, unless the EventableDescriptor associated with fd 4 isnalso deleted before the next call to epoll_wait, events may firenfor fd 3 that were registered with an already deletednEventableDescriptor.nnTherefore, it is necessary to notify EventMachine thatnwhen an EventableDescriptor is closing so that it cannremove it from the event loop.n

Make ScheduleClose() idempotentI think this fixes issue #441.nn8b613d0 changed the `select` timeout to zero in the case wherenNumCloseScheduled > 0. It seems that in certain circumstances (fornexample, if `close_connection` is called in a connection's `unbind`)nNumCloseScheduled would get incremented twice, but only decrementednonce, thus never again reaching zero for the lifetime of the reactor.nnThe user-observed effect was that one CPU core would be pegged at 100%,nbecause the zero `select` timeout caused us to go around the select loopnwithout any pause.nnChanging it so that it is safe to ScheduleClose() multiple times seemsnlike the cleanest solution to the problem.n

Switch from epoll_create to epoll_create1 (#832)The original epoll_create took a size argument as a hint for how muchrnkernel space to allocate for events. Since Linux 2.6.8, the sizernargument is ignored, but must be greater than zero.rnrnSince we also need to set CLOEXEC on the epoll fd, there is a smallrnwindow between epoll_create and fcntl as they are separate functionrncalls. Since Linux 2.6.27 and glibc 2.9, epoll_create1 accepts thernCLOEXEC argument at creation time to eliminate this gap.rnrnThis drops support for epoll on RHEL 5 / CentOS 5, EOL was March 2017.rnrnResolves #770

Improve line_protocol speed (#894)I'm having problems with current line_protocol implementation, causing up to 60% of my overall run time to be spent slicing the message buffer. I've change it to use ``String#each_line`` instead of ``slice`` which proves to be 200x faster:rnrn```Rubyrnrequire 'benchmark'rnrndef new_version(size)rn  buffer = Array.new(size, 'foo 123').join(n)rnrn  buffer.each_line do |line|rnif line[-1] == nrnelsern  buffer = linernendrn  endrnendrnrndef original(size)rn  buffer = Array.new(size, 'foo 123').join(n)rnrn  while buffer.slice!(/(.*?)r?n/) dorn  endrnendrnrnBenchmark.bmbm do |x|rn  x.report('original') { original(100_000) }rn  x.report('new_version')  { new_version(100_000) }rnendrn```rn```rnRehearsal -----------------------------------------------rnoriginal  4.891919   0.103960   4.995879 (  4.993582)rnnew_version   0.026254   0.000005   0.026259 (  0.026250)rn-------------------------------------- total: 5.022138secrnrn  user system  totalrealrnoriginal  4.922760   0.031001   4.953761 (  4.951560)rnnew_version   0.026114   0.000000   0.026114 (  0.026103)rn```rnrnThe only downside is that ``each_line`` always returns the last part of the string, so ``foonbar.each_line`` will yield both ``foo`` and ``bar``. To fix this I just use the fact that ``each_line`` actually returns the line terminators so, if I returns me a string without a new line I know the buffer has ended and the last line is the content of the new buffer.
